{"author":{"id":"b98d1ba9cd7343da96b51f325fc4b59b4eca0be27820f70d2ca5406ac9eed8c1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1590003491,"nonce":"0G2Ypyq+e/w3rmWON4sShVYcEOY=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU2MjIwMzU1NDY=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3045","origin":"github"},"title":"fastq-dump --split-files command isue","message":"Fastq-dump in Galaxy uses the `--split-files` flag. BWA-mem and Snippy were failing for me on a subset of files I downloaded in Galaxy using Fastq-dump, and exported to the command line. Renaming the headers with bbrename from BBtools fixed that issue for me.\n\nI noticed that the help text for `fastq-dump version 2.10.3` advises against this flag in the help command. I'm not however familiar if there were any technical reasons for choosing `--split-files` over `--split-e` \n\nfastq-dump\" version 2.10.3 help text:\n\n\n`--split-files                 Write reads into separate files. Read\n                                     number will be suffixed to the file\n                                     name. NOTE! The `--split-3` option is   #should be --split-e?\n                                     recommended. In cases where not all\n                                     spots have the same number of reads,\n                                     this option will produce files that WILL\n                                     CAUSE ERRORS in most programs which\n                                     process split pair fastq files.\n\n --split-e                     3-way splitting for mate-pairs. For each\n                                     spot, if there are two biological reads\n                                     satisfying filter conditions, the first\n                                     is placed in the `*_1.fastq` file, and\n                                     the second is placed in the `*_2.fastq`\n                                     file. If there is only one biological\n                                     read satisfying the filter conditions,\n                                     it is placed in the `*.fastq` file.All\n                                     other reads in the spot are ignored.\n`","files":null}]}